To Cook,<br><br>
Once again you have presented well laid out thoughts.  I would like to respond to your message, and perhaps clear up any misconceptions on my original posting.<br><br>
In regards to PTSD, yes, every combat soldier does experience it, I believe everyone.  PTSD, is a form of sensory overload, that description fits combat perfectly.  There are two kinds of PTSD according to psychologists.  One is the short lenght type, this is a type most soldiers go through, it usually takes 6 months to get past it according to experts (does anyone really get over it?).  The second type lasts many years after, this type is still seen, sometimes today.  I totally agree, all soldiers go through PTSD.<br><br>
Let me clarify my position on GUILT as related to PTSD.  The type of guilt, I was talking about had nothing to do with the experiences of the average soldier.  I was talking about the guilt that may be experienced by those soldiers that were responsible for violent acts against civilians.  They may feel guilt over what they did.<br>
Vietnam vets don't ever need to feel any guilt over their role in Vietnam.  Cook, it is of my opinion that the average soldier almost never failed in his duties in the field.  The average soldier did the job that was asked of him, the command (at what ever level the conduct and procedure for carrying the war out was decided) was to blame.  You don't get involved in a war of insurgency using the tactics we did.  We fought a Vietnam war, while the North Vietnamese fought a southeast asian war, there is a difference, think about it.  We wasted the best troops America ever fielded in a war of attrition, a style of war that America with its firepower never needs to be part of.<br><br>
If any guilt remains among Vietnam vets, it is survivor guilt, about surviving when others didn't.  There is no need to feel guilty about failing the Vietnamese people.  Yes, we could have done more, protected the Cambodians, helped the boat people, helped orphans, brought our Amerasian children to America, and countless other things, but the average soldier didn't have the power to do that much.  Instead the Nam vet shouldbe  proud of the small things they did, these things count!!  My father is still proud that his Seabee unit built Vietnamese housing, and repaired and took a active part in aiding a orphanage.  He was thrilled to find out that the housing his unit built still houses former South Vietnamese Marines and their families.  What could the average soldier have done?  When military command fought a war of body counts, what was the average soldier to do?  Buck the system and end up in LBJ?  <br><br>
I am a firm believer that ALL VIETNAM VETS need to be very proud of their service.  They fought a war that was unpopular, were a soldier in a time when soldiers were unpopular.  The Vietnam soldier wasn't motivated by promises of land, money, glory etc, he did what was asked of him in a time when America didn't care or hated war and the military.  Cook, guys like you, my father and other vets were only 9% of their generation, yes only 9% served in Vietnam.  My father calls being a Vietnam Vet, &quot;a exclusive club whose membership closed in 1975&quot;.<br><br>
Believe me, I can provide solid evidence, on how the Vietnam soldier was one of the best soldiers America produced, not the worst.  Just look out what he had to endure!!  I agree and have always said that much of PTSD and other problems, were due to coming home and having to face a indifferent America (that indifference is a crime that this country can never make up to the Vietnam Vet!!!), having to be disadvantaged for jobs and benefits, scorned by World War II vets, or as one WW II vet told my father &quot;yours was not a real war&quot;.  This is where the Vietnam vet found problems, he was alone in a sea of indifference.  The real war for Vietnam vets was fought when he returned home.  That is why I try to encourage people in my generation to respect and honor the Vietnam soldier as much as possible.  If he can't get respect from his own generation, maybe my generation can do it!!<br>
Just to clarify any misconceptions, I feel that the Vietnam Vet was some of our best soldiers, soldiers that we misused (thanks to poor planning not in any way to poor fighting) in war and abused at home.  America should be proud of its vets and ashamed of the abuse and indifference that was put on the Vietnam vet.  If I sound a little extreme and foward, it is just that I am the son of a Nam vet and I'm tired of hearing how bad we were in Vietnam.  Vietnam vets were held to a super high standard that is totally unrealistic when it comes to warfare of any type, in any place.  I have the highest respect for the Vietnam vet, honor him as much as possible and try to do my share to convince others on the positive image of Vietnam vets (I studied about the Vietnam War since I was 12 to understand it).<br><br>
Cook, in the Memorial Day thread I posted a poem by a Major Michael O'Donnell (who was MIA and later declared KIA) that was featured in Dear America Letters Home from Vietnam. I believe this dead &quot;brother vet&quot; summed up your feelings about embracing the Vietnam vet, or at least those who paid the ultimate price-check it out if you get the chance.<br><br>
Cook, wear your medals (do it for the 58,000 if you can't do it for you) and be proud.  If the rest of the country give a damn, at least there are a growing number of young people out there (like me-I'm 23) who are proud! Welcome Home!!! <br><br>
   
